<subSubSection box="[199,1016,439,464]" pageId="12" pageNumber="317" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1436,151,752]" box="[199,1016,439,464]" pageId="12" pageNumber="317">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,439,464]" pageId="12" pageNumber="317">Etymology.</emphasis>
Named for its small size; from the Latin “ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brailovsky &amp; Barrera" authorityYear="2017" box="[808,928,440,464]" class="Insecta" family="Nabidae" genus="Alloeorhynchus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="317" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vergrandis">
<emphasis box="[808,928,440,464]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="317">vergrandis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
” small.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="317" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1436,151,752]" pageId="12" pageNumber="317">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,332,476,501]" pageId="12" pageNumber="317">Discussion.</emphasis>
This species is related to 
<taxonomicName authority="Harris" authorityName="Harris" box="[640,914,476,501]" class="Insecta" family="Nabidae" genus="Alloeorhynchus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="317" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigrofasciatus">
<emphasis box="[640,834,476,500]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="317">A. nigrofasciatus</emphasis>
Harris
</taxonomicName>
by having the anterior lobe of the pronotum shiny yellowish orange; the clavus and corium are almost entirely black to dark brown; and connexival segments II–V shiny yellow have a group of black spinules resembling an elongate spot. In 
<taxonomicName box="[1092,1284,548,572]" class="Insecta" family="Nabidae" genus="Alloeorhynchus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="317" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigrofasciatus">
<emphasis box="[1092,1284,548,572]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="317">A. nigrofasciatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the posterior lobe of the pronotum is shiny yellowish orange except for the black semilunar area medially on posterior margin, and the collar is shiny yellowish orange (eventually pale castaneous) (
<figureCitation box="[964,1076,620,645]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 10" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1642,1665]" captionTargetBox="[388,1198,520,1595]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[361,1225,499,1618]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 10. Dorsal view of Alloeorhynchus spp. 1, A. aureus sp. nov. (female). 2 – 3, A. trimacula (Stein) (males). 4, A. macer sp. nov. (female). 5, A. convolutus sp. nov. (female). 6 – 7, A. nigrofasciatus Harris (6, female, 7, male). 8, A. moritzii (Stein) (female). 9, A. nigrolobus Barber (female). 10, A. vergrandis sp. nov. (male)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1036191/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="317">Figs. 6–7</figureCitation>
). In 
<taxonomicName authority="Brailovsky &amp; Barrera, 2017" authorityName="Brailovsky &amp; Barrera" authorityYear="2017" box="[1132,1286,620,644]" class="Insecta" family="Nabidae" genus="Alloeorhynchus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="317" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vergrandis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1132,1286,620,644]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="317">A. vergrandis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1296,1388,621,644]" pageId="12" pageNumber="317" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, the posterior lobe of the pronotum is shiny black to reddish brown with wide yellowish triangular mark lateral to midline, and the collar is shiny reddish brown to dark castaneous (
<figureCitation box="[893,977,692,717]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 10" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1642,1665]" captionTargetBox="[388,1198,520,1595]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[361,1225,499,1618]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 10. Dorsal view of Alloeorhynchus spp. 1, A. aureus sp. nov. (female). 2 – 3, A. trimacula (Stein) (males). 4, A. macer sp. nov. (female). 5, A. convolutus sp. nov. (female). 6 – 7, A. nigrofasciatus Harris (6, female, 7, male). 8, A. moritzii (Stein) (female). 9, A. nigrolobus Barber (female). 10, A. vergrandis sp. nov. (male)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1036191/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="317">Fig. 10</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
